      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Here are the results for the paper **\"Entity-Based Knowledge Conflicts in Question Answering\"** by Longpre et al. (EMNLP 2021):\n\n## Paper Details\n\n"
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "The paper is authored by Shayne Longpre, Kartik Perisetla, Anthony Chen, Nikhil Ramesh, Chris DuBois, and Sameer Singh."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": " "
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "It was published in the Proceedings of the 2021 Conference on Empirical Methods in Natural Language Processing, pages 7052–7063, Online and Punta Cana, Dominican Republic."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "\n\n"
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "The authors are affiliated with Apple and the University of California, Irvine."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "\n\n## Abstract\n\n"
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Knowledge-dependent tasks typically use two sources of knowledge: parametric, learned at training time, and contextual, given as a passage at inference time. To understand how models use these sources together, the authors formalize the problem of knowledge conflicts, where the contextual information contradicts the learned information."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": " "
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Analyzing the behaviour of popular models, they measure their over-reliance on memorized information (the cause of hallucinations), and uncover important factors that exacerbate this behaviour."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": " "
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "They propose a simple method to mitigate over-reliance on parametric knowledge, which minimizes hallucination, and improves out-of-distribution generalization by 4%-7%."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "\n\n## Key Links\n\n- **ACL Anthology**: https://aclanthology.org/2021.emnlp-main.565/\n- **arXiv**: https://arxiv.org/abs/2109.05052\n- **Code (GitHub)**: https://github.com/apple/ml-knowledge-conflicts\n- **Apple ML Research**: https://machinelearning.apple.com/research/entity-knowledge-conflicts\n\n## Additional Notes\n\n"
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "The paper was also presented at the 3rd Workshop on Machine Reading for Question Answering (MRQA) 2021, and was covered in Stanford CS224N (NLP with Deep Learning) Course Lecture, Spring 2022."
      }
    ],
